{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"18b97177-bc4f-4989-a95f-1db30ac0e08f","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple crash reports** rather than .NET-style dumps:\n\n1. **Crash Reports** are saved automatically by macOS:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for files named `<YourApp>_<date>.crash` or `.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n   ```\n\n4. For **symbolicated** crash reports, make sure you build with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false` or keep the `.dSYM` bundle alongside the binary).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1e64932-ef0e-47e5-959c-ba49f57fa0b4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"6094:14BF27:2CF4CF:3A988A:69FFE3D7"},"id":"6fb30214-055c-49a8-9265-51dcc5301823","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:48:15.772Z","parentId":"45ed05c2-3b3f-4108-934e-04b52dc7f092"}
